// dhadhatite_v2.bps — "dhadhatite" qa'ida (tabla)
// Source: bp3-ctests/-gr.dhadhatite (2026-04-20)
// Transposition status: PARTIAL — see UNSUPPORTED.md
//
// This is a beginner's tabla qa'ida with 6 sub-grammars.
// Many BP3 features used here are NOT YET SUPPORTED in BPscript.
// Supported features are translated below; unsupported ones are commented out
// with explicit backlog markers.

@core
@controls

// Production mode: text (bols are non-pitched syllables, not MIDI notes)
// No @alphabet.western — bols are literal sound objects

// =========================================================================
// GRAM#1 — RND: top-level structure
// =========================================================================
// UNSUPPORTED: Time signature in LHS
//   BP3 line: gram#1[1] <100> S <-> 4+4+4+4/4 S64
//   "4+4+4+4/4" is a polymetric time signature annotation on the LHS.
//   BPscript has no equivalent LHS time-signature syntax.
//   NOT YET SUPPORTED in BPscript — backlog item: LHS time-signature annotation
//
// UNSUPPORTED: Bidirectional <-> rules
//   BP3 uses <-> for bidirectional derivation (playback + analysis).
//   BPscript uses <> for bidirectional (->  is L→R default, <> is bidirectional).
//   Translation attempt: <-> → <> (best available approximation)

@mode:random

S <> S64 [weight:100]
S64 <> S1F S2F S1V S2F E32 [weight:100]
S64 <> S1V S2F S1F S2F E32 [weight:100]
S64 <> S1F S2V S1F S2F E32 [weight:100]
S64 <> S1V S2V S1F S2F E32 [weight:100]

-----

// =========================================================================
// GRAM#2 — LIN: structural rules with templates and contexts
// =========================================================================
// UNSUPPORTED: Template markers (= ...) and (: ...) with ++ context prefixes
//   BP3 syntax: (= V8 ) creates a "master bracket" in the template
//               (: V8 ) creates a "slave bracket" that mirrors the master
//               ++ prefixes tokens as context markers
//   BPscript has an @template section with ($N ...) bracket syntax, BUT:
//   - The BP3 (= ...) / (: ...) notation in rule bodies is the old template format
//   - The ++ and + context markers on tokens have NO BPscript equivalent
//   NOT YET SUPPORTED in BPscript:
//     1. (= ... ) / (: ... ) template bracket syntax in rule bodies
//     2. + and ++ context markers as token prefixes
//     3. * separator between template groups in RHS
//
// The rules below strip all template/context syntax, keeping only the
// non-terminal names. This loses all template structure and context disambiguation.

@mode:lin

// gram#2[1]: S1F S2F S1V S2F E32 <-> S1F +S2F (= V8 ) +S2F * (= S1F ++ S2F ) (: V8 ) S1F
// Stripped: S1F S2F S1V S2F E32 -> S1F S2F V8 S2F S1F S2F V8 S1F
S1F S2F S1V S2F E32 -> S1F S2F V8 S2F S1F S2F V8 S1F [weight:100]

// gram#2[2]: S1V S2F S1F S2F E32 <-> (=++ A1 V7 ) +S2F S1F +S2F * (:++ A1 V7 ) * (= ++ S2F ) S1F S1F
// Stripped: S1V S2F S1F S2F E32 -> A1 V7 S2F S1F S2F A1 V7 S2F S1F S1F
S1V S2F S1F S2F E32 -> A1 V7 S2F S1F S2F A1 V7 S2F S1F S1F [weight:100]

// gram#2[3]: S1V S2F S1F S2F E32 <-> (=++ A2 V6 ) +S2F S1F +S2F * (:++ A2 V6 ) * (= ++ S2F ) S1F S1F
// Stripped: S1V S2F S1F S2F E32 -> A2 V6 S2F S1F S2F A2 V6 S2F S1F S1F
// UNSUPPORTED: gram#2[2] and gram#2[3] have the same LHS. LIN mode uses the
// first matching rule — the second would be unreachable in a strict LIN pass.
// In BP3 LIN, all matching rules can be tried. BPscript LIN is first-match.
// NOT YET SUPPORTED: multiple LIN rules with identical LHS (non-deterministic LIN)
// S1V S2F S1F S2F E32 -> A2 V6 S2F S1F S2F A2 V6 S2F S1F S1F [weight:100]

// gram#2[4]: S1F S2V S1F S2F E32 <-> S1F (= V6 + B2 ) S1F +S2F * (= S1F ) * (: V6 + B2 ) S1F S1F
// Stripped: S1F S2V S1F S2F E32 -> S1F V6 B2 S1F S2F S1F V6 B2 S1F S1F
S1F S2V S1F S2F E32 -> S1F V6 B2 S1F S2F S1F V6 B2 S1F S1F [weight:100]

// gram#2[5..10]: All have same LHS S1V S2V S1F S2F E32 — only first is kept.
// The others are commented out for the same reason as gram#2[2] vs [3].
// gram#2[5]: (=++ A1 V11 + B4 ) S1F +S2F * (:++ A1 V11 + B4 ) S1F S1F
S1V S2V S1F S2F E32 -> A1 V11 B4 S1F S2F A1 V11 B4 S1F S1F [weight:100]
// gram#2[6..10] commented out — identical LHS, NOT YET SUPPORTED
// S1V S2V S1F S2F E32 -> A2 V10 B4 S1F S2F A2 V10 B4 S1F S1F [weight:100]
// S1V S2V S1F S2F E32 -> A1 V13 B2 S1F S2F A1 V13 B2 S1F S1F [weight:100]
// S1V S2V S1F S2F E32 -> A2 V12 B2 S1F S2F A2 V12 B2 S1F S1F [weight:100]
// S1V S2V S1F S2F E32 -> A1 V15 S1F S2F A1 V15 S1F S1F [weight:100]
// S1V S2V S1F S2F E32 -> A2 V14 S1F S2F A2 V14 S1F S1F [weight:100]

-----

// =========================================================================
// GRAM#3 — LIN: V-chain (variation cascade V2..V15 → T1/T2)
// =========================================================================
// This sub-grammar is fully translatable. V2..V15 are non-terminals chained
// by LIN derivation. Weights <10> and <100> are mapped to [weight:N].

@mode:lin

V2 -> T2 [weight:100]
V15 -> T1 V14 [weight:10]
V15 -> T2 V13 [weight:100]
V14 -> T1 V13 [weight:10]
V14 -> T2 V12 [weight:100]
V13 -> T1 V12 [weight:10]
V13 -> T2 V11 [weight:100]
V12 -> T1 V11 [weight:10]
V12 -> T2 V10 [weight:100]
V11 -> T1 V10 [weight:10]
V11 -> T2 V9 [weight:100]
V10 -> T1 V9 [weight:10]
V10 -> T2 V8 [weight:100]
V9 -> T1 V8 [weight:10]
V9 -> T2 V7 [weight:100]
V8 -> T1 V7 [weight:10]
V8 -> T2 V6 [weight:100]
V7 -> T1 V6 [weight:10]
V7 -> T2 V5 [weight:100]
V6 -> T1 V5 [weight:10]
V6 -> T2 V4 [weight:100]
V5 -> T1 V4 [weight:10]
V5 -> T2 V3 [weight:100]
V4 -> T1 V3 [weight:10]
V4 -> T2 V2 [weight:100]
V3 -> T1 V2 [weight:10]
V3 -> T2 T1 [weight:100]
V2 -> T1 T1 [weight:10]

-----

// =========================================================================
// GRAM#4 — RND: terminal leaf rules (T1 → dha/-, T2 → dhadha/tite/dheena/teena)
// =========================================================================
// Fully translatable. '-' is the silence symbol (valid in both BP3 and BPscript).

@mode:random

T1 -> dha [weight:100]
T1 -> - [weight:100]
T2 -> dhadha [weight:100]
T2 -> tite [weight:100]
T2 -> dheena [weight:50]
T2 -> teena [weight:50]

-----

// =========================================================================
// GRAM#5 — ORD: context-sensitive terminal rules
// =========================================================================
// UNSUPPORTED: Context markers '+' and '++' as token prefixes
//   BP3: gram#5[1] + B2 <-> +teena
//   The '+' and '++' prefixes mark that this rule fires only in the context
//   where the token was tagged with that prefix in gram#2.
//   BPscript has no equivalent for '+'/'++'  context-prefix mechanism.
//   NOT YET SUPPORTED in BPscript — backlog item: context-prefix propagation
//
// UNSUPPORTED: <-- special rule direction
//   BP3: gram#5[8] ++ S2F <-- ++ dhadhatitedhadhadheena [This rule must be last]
//   <-- means RIGHT→LEFT derivation AND the comment marks it as a constraint
//   ("must be last" = ordering constraint within ORD sub-grammar).
//   BPscript has <- for right-to-left, but no "must be last" ordering constraint.
//   NOT YET SUPPORTED in BPscript — backlog item: ORD rule ordering constraint
//
// UNSUPPORTED: #+ prefix on LHS token
//   BP3: gram#5[6] #+ S1F <-> #+ dhadhatitedhadhadheena
//   '#' marks a "negative context" in Bernard's engine (not the same as
//   BPscript's # comment). No BPscript equivalent.
//   NOT YET SUPPORTED in BPscript — backlog item: negative-context marker '#+'
//
// The rules below strip context markers, translating only the non-terminal
// names and terminal bols. The context disambiguation is completely lost.
// In practice this means: S1F always → dhadhatitedhadhadheena (last rule wins),
// S2F always → dhadhatitedhadhadheena (both gram#5[7] and gram#5[8] map to S2F).

@mode:ord

// gram#5[1]: + B2 <-> +teena  (context marker stripped)
B2 -> teena [weight:100]

// gram#5[2]: + B4 <-> +dhadhateena  (context marker stripped)
// Note: 'dhadhateena' is NOT in gram#4 terminals — it is a composite bol
// used only as a fixed terminal in gram#5 context. Added to alphabet.
B4 -> dhadhateena [weight:100]

// gram#5[3]: ++ A1 <-> ++dha  (context marker stripped)
A1 -> dha [weight:100]

// gram#5[4]: ++ A2 <-> ++dhadha  (context marker stripped)
A2 -> dhadha [weight:100]

// gram#5[5]: ++ A2 <-> ++dheena  (context marker stripped, duplicate LHS)
// A2 -> dheena [weight:50]

// gram#5[6]: #+ S1F <-> #+ dhadhatitedhadhadheena  (#+ marker stripped)
S1F -> dhadhatitedhadhadheena [weight:100]

// gram#5[7]: + S2F <-> + dhadhatitedhadhateena  (context marker stripped)
S2F -> dhadhatitedhadhateena [weight:100]

// gram#5[8]: ++ S2F <-- ++ dhadhatitedhadhadheena  [This rule must be last]
// UNSUPPORTED: <-- direction (right-to-left) + ordering constraint
// In original BP3, this rule fires ONLY when S2F is in a ++ context,
// overriding gram#5[7]. Without context markers, we cannot express this.
// The rule is commented out — if included, it would conflict with gram#5[7].
// NOT YET SUPPORTED: <-- rule direction in BPscript ORD sub-grammar
// S2F <- dhadhatitedhadhadheena

// =========================================================================
// TEMPLATES section
// =========================================================================
// UNSUPPORTED: The TEMPLATES: section in the original uses BP3's old (= ...)
// bracket notation with '+' context markers and '++' positional markers.
// The BPscript @template syntax uses ($N ...) and ? wildcards, but the
// translation from the BP3 format is non-trivial and the context markers
// cannot be represented.
//
// Original TEMPLATES (6 entries) — NOT TRANSLATED.
// NOT YET SUPPORTED in BPscript — backlog item:
//   Full BP3 TEMPLATES format with (=...)/(: ...) bracket notation.
